{
  "Idea": "We propose the creation of 'XTabRobust', a Human-Annotated, Cross-Component Adversarial Benchmark for Table Question Answering (TableQA), designed to systematically evaluate model robustness against realistic, semantically coherent perturbations spanning table headers, cell content, and natural language questions. Unlike prior benchmarks that apply perturbations in isolation or via automated rules, XTabRobust introduces orchestrated adversarial transformations—where modifications in one component (e.g., renaming a header from 'Revenue' to 'Income') trigger consistent, human-validated adjustments in related cells and questions (e.g., changing 'What was the revenue in 2020?' to 'How much income was generated in 2020?'). This ensures logical consistency while challenging models’ ability to maintain alignment across modalities. The benchmark includes over 15,000 annotated instances derived from diverse domains (finance, sports, science) and builds upon high-quality datasets like WTQ, SQA, and FeTaQA. Each instance undergoes multi-stage human annotation: (1) identification of sensitive components, (2) application of one of 12 fine-grained perturbation types (e.g., synonym substitution, unit conversion, negation insertion, structural shuffling, referential ambiguity), and (3) validation of answer-preserving semantics. Crucially, we introduce a novel dimension: cross-component dependency strength, scored per instance to measure how tightly coupled the perturbations are across table and question. This enables researchers to probe whether models rely on shallow heuristics or perform deep, context-aware reasoning. XTabRobust supports three key use cases: (1) fine-grained robustness diagnostics via per-perturbation-type performance breakdowns, (2) stress-testing of retrieval-augmented and LLM-based TableQA systems under coordinated noise, and (3) targeted adversarial training using semantically valid, human-curated examples. We further release a toolkit for perturbation synthesis, model probing, and diagnostic reporting. By exposing critical failure modes in current models—especially their fragility under joint schema-content-question shifts—XTabRobust provides a principled path toward more reliable, real-world-deployable TableQA systems.",
