  "Idea": "We propose 'DepTabQA': a Dynamic Dependency-Aware, Human-Validated Benchmark for Evaluating Systemic Robustness in Table Question Answering. DepTabQA goes beyond static adversarial examples by modeling the TableQA task as a tripartite graph linking headers, cell contents, and natural language questions, where each node represents a semantic element and edges encode functional, referential, and syntactic dependencies. Our core innovation is the introduction of 'Perturbation Dependency Graphs' (PDGs)—structured representations that guide coordinated, semantically consistent edits across all three components. For instance, changing a header from 'Population (2020)' to 'Residents (two years before pandemic)' triggers automatic—but human-validated—adjustments: numerical values remain unchanged (answer-preserving), but associated questions like 'What was the population in 2020?' evolve into 'How many residents lived two years before the pandemic?', while distractor rows may be introduced to test overfitting. DepTabQA includes 18,000 QA triplets drawn from WTQ, SQA, FeTaQA, and financial datasets, each annotated with a PDG and classified along two novel dimensions: (1) 'Ripple Strength'—a continuous score from 0 to 1 measuring how many downstream components must adapt to preserve semantics—and (2) 'Counterfactual Consistency', assessed via paired original/adversarial examples to evaluate answer stability. We define 15 perturbation types organized into three tiers: local (single-component), coupled (two-component), and systemic (all-three), with human annotators ensuring linguistic naturalness and logical validity. Crucially, we release a generative framework that uses PDGs to synthesize new adversarial instances at scale, enabling both evaluation and adversarial training. DepTabQA enables unprecedented diagnostics: e.g., testing whether LLM-based TableQA systems degrade not due to individual perturbations, but when ripple strength exceeds a threshold, indicating poor cross-modal integration. We further introduce 'Dependency Stress Testing', where models are evaluated under increasing average ripple strength to identify breaking points. Applications include diagnosing shallow reasoning, improving training data augmentation, and auditing production systems. Initial experiments suggest current models exhibit <40% accuracy on high-ripple (>0.7) instances despite >85% on originals, revealing critical gaps in real-world reliability.",
  "Title": "DepTabQA: A Dependency-Aware Adversarial Benchmark for Systemic Robustness Evaluation in Table Question Answering",
